The paper deals with algorithmic aspects of cooperative games, which are typically studied in the subfield of game theory (cs.GT). The use of overlapping coalitions and the exploration of the core of the game suggest a focus on multiagent systems and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The study of the problem of deciding if the core of an OCF game is not empty and whether a core payoff division can be found in polynomial time suggests a focus on computational complexity and algorithms (cs.DS). The exploration of conditions that ensure polynomial time algorithms also suggests a focus on theoretical computer science and machine learning (cs.LG). Finally, the study of a specific class of OCF games, Linear Bottleneck Games, suggests a focus on mathematical analysis and optimization (cs.MA).
